@markusschaber, regardless of how obsolete and outdated Windows Forms is, it's widely used by applications which could benefit from being ported to .NET Core. I'm assuming that simply making Windows Forms available in .NET Core on Windows shouldn't be a huge challenge (I may be wrong). The same could be argued for WPF.

The "fresh, future-proof UI framework, which is platform independent" which you're asking for is a *huge* undertaking (just look at the history of this in Java or other technology spaces). Of course it would be great to have this one day, but I'm more concerned with the short- and medium-term here.

.NET Core is clearly still focused on server workloads at the moment, and that's fine. But as it starts to jump ahead of .NET Framework and a gap starts to appear, it may make sense to at least allow Windows applications to be ported, depending on how much effort it would involve. Someone could also create bindings for Similarly, someone could set up bindings for Gtk and/or Qt to allow for cross-platform GUI (not sure what state Gtk# is in and what it would take to bring it to .NET Core).

I've actually been thinking that we should review and consider a version of this PR as part of webroot.  It seems to be fundamentally part of that plugin's ambit: I have a webroot directory here, it just happens to be shared with some other systems.

What I'm not sure about is whether we should stay specific to rsync, or consider a more general case, which is, "once the webroot is configured to pass challenges, run command X to push it to deployment".  That could be rsync, but it could also conceivably be other operations, such as clearing a cache, tweaking a firewall, etc.  So we `--webroot` could have flags like `--webroot-pre-validate` and `--webroot-post-validate` that take scripts as arguments, and are run before and after DV.  A `--rsync` flag could exist in addition, and use most of the same mechanics internally (a crafted `subprocess.Popen` rather than a raw call to a script).

