@soumith now that it's still in its infancy, it's worth examining one key point though (let me know if this belongs in a separate issue): once you have dynamic computation graphs (which are prevalent in NLP) you fundamentally have to mathematically define behavior somehow.

Yeah, ONNX really should have a CuDNN like API where certain common operations are well-standardized (which lets hardware vendors build supporting ASICs or instructions) but it would be unwise to leverage the fact that what we have is essentially a graph of self contained (sometimes stateful) computations. If ONNX also provides the primitives for those computations (presumably arithmetic primitives) compilers can become increasingly smart about how to optimize and parallelize those operations. This lets most use cases use the well-defined (and typically hardware accelerated) operations and advanced used cases leverage custom operators that we can still reason about in the IR.

I strongly believe this approach should be taken as support for more sophisticated graphs and operations comes about. Since it allows future architectures and techniques to leverage ONNX without requiring the format to change really frequently to incorporate new techniques.

