@emtrane hmm, `Subscription.cancel()` is provided when an `<a name="cancel">` link is present in Recurly's response describing the subscription. That error will certainly happen if the `Subscription` instance has only been instantiated, as the service hasn't had a chance to tell you if it's eligible to be cancelled yet. The `cancel()` method should be available when the subscription is the result of a `get()` (as in the example) or has been used in an `account.subscribe()` call (as in the library's tests).

Try turning on debug logging in your code and seeing if the `Subscription` response that creates your subscription instance has an `<a name="cancel">` link.

If you're using `get()` as in the example but the link is missing from the response, that could mean that subscription isn't in a state where it can be cancelled (though mostly that's just when it's already been cancelled, IIRC).
